[{"id":39541,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$4$","$8.4$","$2$","$6.2$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & P_{\\text {input }}=V i=100 \\mathrm{~W} \\\\ & \\eta=\\frac{P_{\\text {out }}}{P_{\\text {input }}}=0.916\\end{aligned}$<br/>$\\begin{aligned} & P_{\\text {out }}=91.6 \\mathrm{~W} \\\\ & \\text { Loss }=100-91.6=8.4 \\mathrm{~J} / \\mathrm{s}=2 \\mathrm{cal} / \\mathrm{s}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (3 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39511,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Let the EMF of the cell be $E$ and its internal resistance be $r$.<br><br>The current $I$ in the circuit is given by $I = \\dfrac{E}{R + r}$.<br><br>For the first case, $R_1 = 5\\ \\Omega$ and $I_1 = 0.25\\text{ A}$:<br><br>$0.25 = \\dfrac{E}{5 + r} \\Rightarrow E = 0.25(5 + r)$<br><br>For the second case, $R_2 = 2\\ \\Omega$ and $I_2 = 0.5\\text{ A}$:<br><br>$0.5 = \\dfrac{E}{2 + r} \\Rightarrow E = 0.5(2 + r)$<br><br>Equating the expressions for $E$:<br><br>$0.25(5 + r) = 0.5(2 + r)$<br><br>$5 + r = 2(2 + r)$<br><br>$5 + r = 4 + 2r$<br><br>$r = 1\\ \\Omega$<br><br>Answer: $1$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (05 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39589,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>For first case:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>W</mi></math>     ...(i)</p><p>Now, equivalent resistance of the combination will be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mi>R</mi></mstyle><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mn>2</mn></mstyle></mfrac></mstyle><mrow><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>For second case:</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>W</mi><mo>'</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mfrac></math>    ...(ii)</p><p>From (i) &amp; (ii), we get<br/><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>W</mi><mo>'</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39720,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Here assume current as</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/93dac662-2a12-4738-9d66-7ca0a830ecb6-image.png\" style=\"width: 277px; height: 204px;\" /></p><p>By KVL in the outer loop</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>9</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn><mi>i</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>45</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39619,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img height=\"294\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7da8b401-9192-484c-ac93-95a57f723a38.png\" width=\"407\" /></p><p>It is given that&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p><p>Using the formula of resistance,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mi>A</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39569,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"We know $\\mathrm{R}=\\frac{\\rho l}{\\mathrm{~A}}, \\mathrm{R} \\propto \\frac{l}{\\mathrm{r}^2}$\nAs we starch the wire, its length will increase but its radius will decrease keeping the volume constant\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{i}}=\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{f}} \\\\\n& \\pi \\mathrm{r}^2 l=\\pi \\frac{\\mathrm{r}^2}{4} l_{\\mathrm{f}} \\\\\n& l_{\\mathrm{f}}=4 l \\\\\n& \\frac{\\mathrm{R}_{\\text {new }}}{\\mathrm{R}_{\\text {old }}}=\\left(\\frac{4 l}{\\frac{\\mathrm{r}^2}{4}}\\right) \\frac{\\mathrm{r}^2}{l}=16 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{R}_{\\text {new }}=16 \\mathrm{R} \\\\\n\\therefore & \\mathrm{x}=16\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39571,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$1: 2$","$2: 1$","$4: 1$","$1: 1$"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/bJnsYPHo3Gt93ndG0ZoF4RrHtAJXp7x50q8DEvi6sic.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{\\mathrm{i}_1}{\\mathrm{i}_2}=\\frac{10}{5}=\\frac{2}{1} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1}{\\mathrm{P}_2}=\\frac{\\mathrm{i}_1^2 \\mathrm{R}_1}{\\mathrm{i}_2^2 \\mathrm{R}_2}=\\left(\\frac{2}{1}\\right)^2 \\times \\frac{5}{10}=\\frac{2}{1}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39737,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>p</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8230;</mo><mfenced><mn>2</mn></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>s</mi><mi>p</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><msup><mi>p</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi></math></p><p>for minimum value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>R</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>R</mi><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><msup><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39715,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>010</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>033</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>003</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>042</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>16</mn><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>15</mn><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>20</mn><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>T</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>Assuming <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>, as a general convention.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>16</mn><mn>20</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#945;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>003</mn><msup><mmultiscripts><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mprescripts></mprescripts><none></none><mo>&#8728;</mo></mmultiscripts><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39692,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> deflection method cannot be used for determining the resistance of the galvanometer.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;deflection method can be used and in this case the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>G</mi></math> equals to twice the value of shunt resistance(s).","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> deflection method can be used and in this case, the G equals to three times the value of shunt resistance(s).","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> deflection method can be used and in this case the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>G</mi></math> value equals to the shunt resistance(s)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/21657d2e-ca03-46ae-97bd-0cc41add82b3-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 148px;\" /></p><p>If a large resistance <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi></math>&nbsp;is connected with a battery, then current will be approximately <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>&#949;</mi><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math>, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> will remain almost constant.</p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>1</mn><mrow><mi>st</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msup></math> case, only <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi>G</mi></mfenced></math> is connected <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>g</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi></math></p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>2</mn><mrow><mi>nd</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></msup></math> case,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>g</mi></msub><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>-</mo><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>g</mi></msub></mrow></mfenced><mi>S</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>g</mi></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mi>S</mi><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>g</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>S</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mi>i</mi></math></p><p>If <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mfenced><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>g</mi></msub></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mfenced><msub><mi>i</mi><mi>g</mi></msub></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mi>S</mi><mrow><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>g</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>S</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mi>i</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>g</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>S</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39679,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Using the conditions of a balanced wheatstone bridge and adding the end correction.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>l</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>e</mi></mrow><mrow><mfenced><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>e</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>l</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>e</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mn>15</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>43</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>102</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>45</mn></mrow></mfenced></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>57</mn><mn>45</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>15</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>19</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39672,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Each wire has resistance,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#961;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Eight wire in parallel, then equivalent resistance is</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>r</mi><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Single copper wire of length <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi></math> has resistance&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>R</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>&#961;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>l</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msubsup><mi>d</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfrac></math>.</p><p>Comparing both equations,&nbsp;we get,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#961;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>8</mn><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msubsup><mi>d</mi><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#961;</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi>d</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>d</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39800,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>V</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>220</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>220</mn></mrow><mn>25</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>44</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>44</mn></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>220</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>220</mn></mrow><mn>100</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>22</mn></math><br /><br />As resistance are in series current through them will be same.<br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><msup><mi>i</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msub><mi>R</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>44</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>44</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>22</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>22</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mn>1</mn></mfrac></math></p><p>Therefore, among the given options, the option matching is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>&#160;</mi><msub><mi>P</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">W</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (12 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39573,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$10.5 \\Omega$ and $1.14 \\mathrm{~A}$","$12 \\Omega$ and $1 \\mathrm{~A}$","$10.5 \\Omega$ and $1 \\mathrm{~A}$","$12 \\Omega$ and $11.4 \\mathrm{~A}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Here $\\mathrm{R}_2, \\mathrm{R}_3, \\mathrm{R}_4$ are in parallel\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{R}_{234}}=\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{R}_2}+\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{R}_3}+\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{R}_4} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{R}_{234}=2 \\Omega\n\\end{aligned}$\n$R_{234}$ is in series with $R_1$ so\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{eq}}=\\mathrm{R}_{234}+\\mathrm{R}_1=2+10=12 \\Omega \\\\\n& \\mathrm{i}=\\frac{12}{12}=1 \\mathrm{Amp}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39826,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["<math><mn>910</mn><mi> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>990</mn><mi> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>505</mn><mi> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>","<math><mn>550</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dcef6876-24e7-4042-ad25-833e1ed41394-image.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 148px;\" /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mi>a</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>b</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>100</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>&#160;</mi></math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>a</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn></mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mi>b</mi> <mi>a</mi> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mi>l</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mn>110</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>100</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow> <mi>l</mi> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mi>l</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mn>110</mn><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi>l</mi></mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msup> <mi>l</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> <mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>11000</mn><mo>+</mo><msup> <mi>l</mi> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>100</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>110</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>l</mi></mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mn>200</mn><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>11000</mn></mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mrow> <mn>110</mn></mrow> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mn>55</mn></mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>55</mn></mrow> <mrow> <mn>45</mn></mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mi>a</mi> <mi>b</mi> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>550</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi>b</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>450</mn><mtext>&#8201;</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#937;</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39758,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["Multimeter shows an equal deflection in both cases i.e., before and after reversing the probes if the chosen component is resistor.","Multimeter shows NO deflection in both cases i.e. before and after reversing the probes if the chosen component is capacitor","Multimeter shows a deflection, accompanied by a splash of light out of connected component in one direction and NO deflection on reversing the probes if the chosen component is LED","Multimeter shows NO deflection in both cases i.e. before and after reversing the probes is the chsosen component is metal wire."],"answer":1,"solution":"Multimeter shows NO deflection in both cases i.e. before and after reversing the probes if the chosen component is capacitor.\r\nMultimeter shows deflection when it connects with capacitor\r\nIf we assume that LED has negligiable resistance then multimeter shows no deflection for the forward bias but when it connects in reverse direction, it break down occurs so splash of light out.\r\nThe resistance of metal wire may be taken zero, so no deflection in multimeter\r\nNo matter, how we connect the resistance across multimeter It shows same deflection.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39873,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$\\frac{\\rho l}{\\pi a}-\\frac{\\rho l}{\\pi(a+b)}$","$\\frac{\\rho l}{a}-\\frac{\\rho l}{(a+b)}$","$\\frac{\\rho l}{2 \\pi a}-\\frac{\\rho l}{2 \\pi(a+b)}$","$\\frac{\\rho l}{2 \\pi(a-b)}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Choosing $A$ as origin,\n$$\n\\begin{gathered}\nE=\\rho j=\\rho \\frac{1}{2 \\pi r^2} \\\\\nV_C-V_B=-\\frac{\\rho l}{2 \\pi} \\int_a^{(a+b)} \\frac{1}{r^2} d r=\\frac{\\rho l}{2 \\pi}\\left[\\frac{1}{(a+b)}-\\frac{1}{a}\\right] \\\\\nV_B-V_C=\\frac{\\rho l}{2 \\pi}\\left[\\frac{1}{a}-\\frac{1}{(a+b)}\\right]\n\\end{gathered}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":39891,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$40 \\Omega$","$20 \\Omega$","$400 \\Omega$","$200 \\Omega$"],"answer":0,"solution":"$R_{\\text {hot }}=\\frac{V^2}{P}=\\frac{200 \\times 200}{100}=400 \\Omega$\ncold resistance $=R_{\\text {hot }} / 10=400 / 10=40 \\Omega$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":39885,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$\\frac{q}{1+\\frac{z_1}{z_2}}$","$\\frac{q}{1+\\frac{z_2}{z_1}}$","$\\mathrm{q} \\frac{z_1}{z_2}$","$\\mathrm{q} \\frac{z_2}{z_1}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$q_1 Z_1=q_2 Z_2$\n$q=q_1+q_2$\n$\\therefore q_2=\\frac{q}{1+\\frac{Z_2}{Z_1}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":39875,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$0.27 A P_2$ to $P_1$","$0.03 A P_1$ to $P_2$","$0.03 A P_2$ to $P_1$","$0.27 \\mathrm{~A} \\mathrm{P} P_1$ to $P_2$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& V_{P_2}-V_{P_1}=\\frac{\\frac{5}{2}+\\frac{0}{10}-\\frac{2}{1}}{\\frac{1}{2}+\\frac{1}{10}+\\frac{1}{1}} \\\\\n& I=\\frac{V_{P_2}-V_{P_1}}{10}=0.03 \\text { from } P_2 \\rightarrow P_1\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/pbSNzkZRi6-ZJlBoRxqYD6XQr7THDLzGxp9K2YGDHg0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":39860,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Current Electricity","question":"","options":["$5.5$ ampere","$0.5$ ampere","$0.004$ ampere","$0.045$ ampere"],"answer":3,"solution":"The current that will given full scale deflection in the absence of the shunt is nearly equal to the current through the galvanometer when shunt is connected i.e. $\\mathrm{I}_{\\mathrm{g}}$\nAs $I_g=\\frac{I S}{G+S}$\n$=\\frac{5.5 \\times 1}{120+1}=0.045$ ampere","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null}]